  "doc_id": "23995",
  "text": "Our patient experienced an acute hypertensive crisis followed by cardiovascular collapse precipitated by the administration of intravenous glucocorticoids for an allergic reaction. Glucocorticoids increase circulating catecholamines through a variety of mechanisms, which include inhibition of catechol O-methyl transferase [CITATION_1] , induction of pheylethanolamine-N-methyltrasnferase [CITATION_2] and increase tyrosine hydroxylase kinase activation [CITATION_3] (See Figure 2) . The patient returned to the emeregency department, in a hypertensive crisis requiring intravenous blood pressure medications, pulmonary edema and type A non-ketotic lactic acidosis which is a presenting feature of pheochromoctyoma. Our patient had a mixed tumor which produced both epinephrine and norepinephrine, both which are equally responsible for an elevated systolic blood pressure. The production of lactic acid is the direct result of the norepinephrine causing peripheral vasoconstriction, in the presence of epinephrine which increases the metabolic needs of the target tissue. The discordance between oxygen supply and demand results in tissue anoxia, glycogenolyis and pyruvate metabolism leading to the generation of lactic acid [CITATION_4] . Glycogenolyis and increased resistance to insulin from catecholamine excess also explains her glucose level of 734 mg/dL.",
